column12: description:{"en":"From Drawn \u0026 Quarterly:\n\nShowa: A History of Japan is a work of Shigeru Mizuki's meticulously researched historical portrait of twentieth-century Japan. This series deals with the period leading up to World War II
column13: a time of high unemployment and other economic hardships caused by the Great Depression. Mizuki's photo-realist style effortlessly brings to life the Japan of the 1920s and 1930s
column14: depicting bustling city streets and abandoned graveyards with equal ease.\nWhen the Showa era began
column15: Mizuki himself was just a few years old
column16: so his earliest memories coincide with the earliest events of the time. With his trusty narrator Rat Man
column17: Mizuki brings history into the realm of the personal
column20: for young audiences as well as more mature readers. As he describes the militarization that leads up to World War II
column21:
Mizuki's stance toward war is thoughtful and often downright critical―his portrayal of the Nanjing Massacre clearly paints the incident  as an atrocity. Mizuki's Showa is a beautifully told history that tracks how technological developments and the country's shifting economic stability had a role in shaping Japan's foreign policy in the early twentieth century.

[Official English](https://drawnandquarterly.com/books/showa-1926-1939/)

- **Won the 13th Kodansha Manga Award for Seinen/General in 1989**"}
